@{
    ViewBag.Title = "Home Page";
}
@section featured {
    <section class="featured">
        <div class="content-wrapper">
            <hgroup class="title">
                <h1>Building Agnostic Clients Through the Power of HTTP</h1><br />
                <h2>by Anthony van der Hoorn and Nik Molnar</h2>
            </hgroup>
            <p>
                How HTTP can be used to foster an eco-system where both client and server 
                are able to adapt and evolve. Using concepts such as HATEOAS (Hypertext As 
                The Engine Of Application State), Feature Toggles, Media Types and HTTP
                know how.
            </p>
            <p>
                This session will explore the lessons learned building the client for 
                <a href="http://getglimpse.com">Glimpse</a>, an open source diagnostics 
                and debugging tool for ASP.NET web developers. This 200 level session 
                will cover many pragmatic steps you can take to move your client towards 
                a server agnostic, decoupled architecture which will allow for independent 
                evolution of both the server and client.
            </p>
        </div>
    </section>
}
<h3>What we will be covering :</h3>
<ol class="round">
    <li class="zero">
        <h5>@Html.ActionLink("Introduction", MVC.Slide.Actions.Index(MVC.Slide.Views.ViewNames.Introduction))</h5>
        What Glimpse is and what problem we need to solve (many clients vs many servers) @Html.ActionLink("More...", MVC.Slide.Actions.Index(MVC.Slide.Views.ViewNames.Introduction))
    </li>

    <li class="one">
        <h5>@Html.ActionLink("CORS/JSONP", MVC.Slide.Actions.Index(MVC.Slide.Views.ViewNames.Jsonp))</h5>
        We don’t know where our request is coming from so we need to be able to work with any domain @Html.ActionLink("More...", MVC.Slide.Actions.Index(MVC.Slide.Views.ViewNames.Jsonp))
    </li>

    <li class="two">
        <h5>@Html.ActionLink("Resource Description", MVC.Slide.Actions.Index(MVC.Slide.Views.ViewNames.ResourceDescription))</h5>
        Now we know that we can work with any domain, we need to know which resources are available @Html.ActionLink("More...", MVC.Slide.Actions.Index(MVC.Slide.Views.ViewNames.ResourceDescription))
    </li>

    <li class="three">
        <h5>@Html.ActionLink("Initial Metadata Request", MVC.Slide.Actions.Index(MVC.Slide.Views.ViewNames.InitialRequest))</h5>
        Next, how do we even know where to go for our initial system metadata @Html.ActionLink("More...", MVC.Slide.Actions.Index(MVC.Slide.Views.ViewNames.InitialRequest))
    </li>

    <li class="four">
        <h5>@Html.ActionLink("Uri Templates", MVC.Slide.Actions.Index(MVC.Slide.Views.ViewNames.UriTemplates))</h5>
        Even though we know resources, the different data can be injected into the URI’s hence we need a form of templates @Html.ActionLink("More...", MVC.Slide.Actions.Index(MVC.Slide.Views.ViewNames.UriTemplates))
    </li>

    <li class="five">
        <h5>@Html.ActionLink("Media Types", MVC.Slide.Actions.Index(MVC.Slide.Views.ViewNames.MediaTypes))</h5>
        Now that we can start getting data, how do we know what data we can support @Html.ActionLink("More...", MVC.Slide.Actions.Index(MVC.Slide.Views.ViewNames.MediaTypes))
    </li>

    <li class="six">
        <h5>@Html.ActionLink("Resource Relationships", MVC.Slide.Actions.Index(MVC.Slide.Views.ViewNames.ResourceRelationships))</h5>
